    "source_sections": {
      "references": "[Po18] P\\'{o}lya, Georg, Zur arithmetischen {U}ntersuchung der {P}olynome. Math. Z. (1918), 143--148.",
      "remarks": "Schinzel deduced from P\\'{o}lya's theorem \\cite{Po18} (that the sequence of $k$-smooth integers has unbounded gaps) that this is true with $p_1\\cdots p_k$ replaced by $p_1\\cdots p_{k-1}p_{k+1}$. \n\nThis is unknown even for $k=2$ - that is, is it true that in every interval of $6$ (sufficiently large) consecutive integers there must exist one with at least $3$ prime factors?\n\nWeisenberg has observed that Dickson's conjecture implies the answer is no if we replace $p_1\\cdots p_k$ with $p_1\\cdots p_k-1$. Indeed, let $L_k$ be the lowest common multiple of all integers at most $p_1\\cdots p_k$. By Dickson's conjecture there are infinitely many $n'$ such that $\\frac{L_k}{m}n'+1$ is prime for all $1\\leq m<p_1\\cdots p_k$. It follows that, if $n=L_kn'+1$, then all integers in $[n,n+p_1\\cdots p_k-1)$ have at most $k$ prime factors."
    },
